FBIS4-15404 "drsov068_b_94029" FBIS-SOV-94-068 Daily Report 7 Apr 1994 RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS Media Issues New Department To Grant Press Access to Administration New Department To Grant Press Access to Administration LD0704151994 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 1200 GMT 7 Apr 94 LD0704151994 Moscow Russian Television Network Russian BFN [From the "Vesti" newscast] [Text] [Correspondent P. Korovyakovskiy] Lots of secret things have become known in recent years. We now know about underground towns, about the bugs in the American Embassy, and even about the anti-aircraft system. Probably there is only one thing that we do not know much about: What is happening deep within the president's administration and how his, frankly speaking, large apparatus works and what it is doing. Meanwhile, sociologists believe that it is precisely because there is such an information vacuum that the authorities are often unable to explain the logic of economic and political reforms to the population, and the laws, programs, and directives that are prepared. [Begin recording] [P. Filippov, head of the Directorate for Information Services, in progress] ...come as a surprise to society. There is no stage of previous discussion of them in the press or on radio and TV. [end recording] [Korovyakovskiy] The Directorate for Information Services, a new structure under the president headed by Petr Filippov, from now on intends to regularly inform the press precisely on everyday administrative matters. The journalists that were invited to today's news conference in the former CPSU building were promised access to all the sub-departments of the service and to all officials. Petr Filippov promised that those officials of the presidential staff that refuse to give an interview will be made to do it, but not by using methods favored by the former owners of these halls.
